## Migration: `BackgroundProcessor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

| Location | Pattern | Issue in .NET 8 |
|----------|---------|-----------------|
| `Stop()` → `_workerThread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow + cleanup | Exception never thrown |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

### Why This Breaks

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+. The `ThreadAbortException` catch block **never fires**, so `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` never runs on forced stop. The `Thread.ResetAbort()` call also throws.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — replaces ThreadAbortException handler
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we simply continue to the
                // loop condition, which will exit naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for graceful exit (same as original)
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        _cts.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

---

### Key Changes Explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs; a bool can't unblock `WaitOne`/`Sleep` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal instead of forcible injection |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | The exception type thrown by `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` and cancellation-aware APIs |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | Not needed — `OperationCanceledException` doesn't auto-rethrow like `ThreadAbortException` did |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` + check | `_workerThread.Join(2s)` | Blocks until thread exits or timeout — cleaner and race-free |

---

### Critical Pitfall: `GetNextItem()` Must Cooperate

If `GetNextItem()` blocks (e.g., on a `BlockingCollection` or socket), cancellation **will not interrupt it** unless you pass the token:

```csharp
// ❌ Won't respond to cancellation while blocked
var item = _queue.Take();

// ✅ Throws OperationCanceledException when token is cancelled
var item = _queue.Take(token);

// ✅ For Thread.Sleep replacements
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(millisecondsTimeout);
```

If `GetNextItem()` calls unmodifiable blocking code, wrap it in a child process and use `Process.Kill` as a last resort.

### Other Pitfalls

- **Dispose the `CancellationTokenSource`** — it holds timer/callback resources. The `Stop()` method above does this.
- **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException` silently** in inner methods — only catch it at the top-level loop as shown.
- **Cancellation is not instant** — it only fires at the next checkpoint. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` between expensive steps inside `ProcessItem` if responsiveness matters.
